A motivic study of generalized Burniat surfaces

Chris Peters Discrete Mathematics, Technische Universiteit Eindhoven, Postbus 513, 5600 MB Eindhoven, Netherlands. c.a.m.peters@tue.nl
(Date: 7 September 2017)
Abstract.

Generalized Burniat surfaces are surfaces of general type with pg=qsubscript𝑝𝑔𝑞p_{g}=q and Euler number e=6𝑒6e=6 obtained by a variant of Inoue’s construction method for the classical Burniat surfaces. I prove a variant of the Bloch conjecture for these surfaces. The method applies also to the so-called Sicilian surfaces introduced in [3]. This implies that the Chow motives of all of these surfaces are finite–dimensional in the sense of Kimura.

Key words and phrases:
Algebraic cycles, Chow groups, finite-dimensional motives, Burniat surfaces, Inoue surfaces, Sicilian surfaces
1991 Mathematics Subject Classification:
14C15, 14C25, 14C30 14J29.

1. Introduction

Quite recently in [3] I. Bauer et. al. have investigated a generalization of Inoue’s construction [7] of the classical Burniat surfaces [6]. These surfaces are minimal, of general type and have invariants pg=q=0,1,2formulae-sequencesubscript𝑝𝑔𝑞012p_{g}=q=0,1,2 or 333.

Recall that the Chow group 𝖢𝖧ksubscript𝖢𝖧𝑘\mathop{\mathsf{CH}}\nolimits_{k} is said to be ”trivial”, if the natural cycle class map 𝖢𝖧k↪H2​k↪subscript𝖢𝖧𝑘subscript𝐻2𝑘\mathop{\mathsf{CH}}\nolimits_{k}\hookrightarrow H_{2k} is injective. The kernel of the cycle class map 𝖢𝖧khomsuperscriptsubscript𝖢𝖧𝑘hom\mathop{\mathsf{CH}}\nolimits_{k}^{\rm hom} can be investigated by means of the Abel–Jacobi map 𝖢𝖧khom→Jk→superscriptsubscript𝖢𝖧𝑘homsuperscript𝐽𝑘\mathop{\mathsf{CH}}\nolimits_{k}^{\rm hom}\to J^{k}, where the target is the k𝑘k-th intermediate Jacobian. Its kernel is denoted 𝖢𝖧kAJsuperscriptsubscript𝖢𝖧𝑘AJ\mathop{\mathsf{CH}}\nolimits_{k}^{\rm AJ}. If this vanishes, this has strong consequences. For instance for surfaces this implies pg=0subscript𝑝𝑔0p_{g}=0 and the Albanese map is an isomorphism up to torsion. The converse is Bloch’s conjecture [5]. In a follow-up study [4] this conjecture has been verified for the generalized Burniat surfaces, i.e 𝖢𝖧0hom=0superscriptsubscript𝖢𝖧0hom0\mathop{\mathsf{CH}}\nolimits_{0}^{\rm hom}=0.

These generalized Burniat surfaces Y=X/G𝑌𝑋𝐺Y=X/G are all quotients of X𝑋X by a freely acting abelian group G≃(𝐙/2​𝐙)3similar-to-or-equals𝐺superscript𝐙2𝐙3G\simeq(\mathbf{Z}/2\mathbf{Z})^{3} and where (X,G)𝑋𝐺(X,G) is a so called Burniat hypersurface pair (X,G)𝑋𝐺(X,G): X𝑋X is a hypersurface in a product A𝐴A of three elliptic curves having at most nodes as singularities and G𝐺G is an abelian group acting freely on A𝐴A and leaving X𝑋X invariant. The surface X𝑋X is also called Burniat hypersurface. These come in 161616 families, enumerated SS1subscriptSS1\SS_{1}–SS16subscriptSS16\SS_{16}. The classical Burniat surface belongs to the 444-parameter family SS2subscriptSS2\SS_{2}. Also the family SS1subscriptSS1\SS_{1} is 444-dimensional. The remaining families have only 333 parameters coming from varying the elliptic curve. This implies that the equation of X𝑋X in these cases is uniquely determined, contrary to the first two where there is a pencil of hypersurfaces invariant under G𝐺G. The surfaces Y𝑌Y have at most nodal singularities. For simplicity I assume in this note that Y𝑌Y, and hence X𝑋X is smooth, which is generically the case. However, none of the arguments is influenced by the presence of nodal singularities.

In [10] it has been remarked that the main theorem of loc. cit. yields the Bloch conjecture for the classical Burniat surfaces. The goal of this paper is to apply the same methods to all Burniat hypersurfaces. In particular, one obtains a short proof of the Bloch conjecture in the appropriate cases.

To state the result, let me recall that the Chow motive h​(X)ℎ𝑋h(X) is the pair (X,Δ)𝑋Δ(X,\Delta) where Δ⊂X×XΔ𝑋𝑋\Delta\subset X\times X is the diagonal considered as a (degree 00) self-correspondence of X𝑋X. As a self-correspondence it is an idempotent in the ring Corr0(X)superscriptCorr0𝑋\mathop{\rm Corr}\nolimits^{0}(X) of degree 00 self-correspondences.

If a finite group G𝐺G acts on X𝑋X, any character χ𝜒\chi of the group defines an idempotent

Note that the trivial character gives the motive h​(X/G)ℎ𝑋𝐺h(X/G) of the Burniat hypersurface. The main result now reads as follows:

2. Preliminaries

2.1. A criterion for finite dimensional motives

The general situation of [10] concerns smooth d𝑑d-dimensional complete intersections X𝑋X inside a smooth projective manifold M𝑀M of dimension d+r𝑑𝑟d+r for which Lefschetz’ conjecture B​(M)𝐵𝑀B(M) holds. This conjecture is known to hold for projective space and for abelian varieties and so in particular for the situation in this note.

Recall also that in this situation, with i:X↪M:𝑖↪𝑋𝑀i:X\hookrightarrow M the inclusion, the fixed and variable cohomology is defined as follows.

and that one has a direct sum decomposition

which is orthogonal with respect to the intersection product. In [12] I explained that validity of B​(M)𝐵𝑀B(M) implies the existence of a motive h​(X)var=(X,πvar)ℎsuperscript𝑋var𝑋superscript𝜋varh(X)^{\rm var}=(X,\pi^{\rm var}) such that πvarsuperscript𝜋var\pi^{\rm var} induces projection onto variable cohomology.
